snippet.textDisplay:
I already posted this in someone else's reply but here is my 2 cents:


My assumption is Pilot, Machine error, & weather caused this:
I think the pilot got disorientated due to the heavy fog and thought he was going up instead of down (This happened with a Boeing 737, where 2 pilots got dis-configured and cause the plane to crash. This video references what I am talking about: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=24Fe1wMy-9Y )
For the Helicopter, the speed clocked in is extremely high and if they were both dropping altitude & raising speed, then there should of been warnings (IE: "Terrain Below: Pull up" or a signal indicating too much speed). I think this is maybe a part that added to the confusion and it offers much more of a probable cause if this is true.


*Note that i'm not familiar with helicopters, this is just my knowledge of general aviation from watching a variety of aviation based videos. Here are also some video that cover the subject:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HhYxBzJEUr8
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=B0pQfgi9ZqU
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OArVMTPNm5o

snippet.textDisplay: The crash site was at 1,085 feet so the helicopter was clear of terrain when it ascended to 2,300 feet. At 2,300 feet the pilot may have been in the clouds, not a good situation. But being not just an instrument rated pilot but an instrument instructor he should have been able to manage flying using the instruments on the helicopter, even if the aircraft wasn't rated for instrument flight. Either he lost control or was hastily trying to get below the cloud layer to get reoriented regarding his location and flew at high speed into the terrain. A scary thought is that for a few seconds prior to impact the passengers may have known they were in very serious trouble. I can't imagine being on that helicopter, helpless to do anything about the situation.
